Source: Yahoo Asia News, 20 Sep 2000 [edited

Hand, Foot And Mouth Disease Now A Notifiable Disease in Johor Bahru
-------------------------------------------
Malaysia: It is now mandatory for government and private hospitals in Johor
Bahru to report cases of hand, foot and mouth (HFM) disease to the state
Health Department. This puts the disease on a similar level with other
contagious diseases, including dengue, food poisoning, measles, malaria and
HIV, which come under the "notifiable disease" category.
As of last Friday [15 Sep 2000, there had been 158 cases of the HFM disease
recorded between January and August, reports The Star newspaper. Senior
assistant health director (epidemiology) Dr Nooraini Baba, said the
department needs the reports to compile an official data[base on the cases
and to determine whether there is an outbreak. Dr Nooraini added while the
disease
is endemic, parents could prevent their children from contracting the virus
by maintaining a high level of cleanliness in their homes and personal
hygiene. She advised parents not to take children to crowded places such as
supermarkets, public swimming pools, nurseries and day-care centres with
recent cases of the disease.
In a related development, Singapore now has another 43 new cases of HFM
disease found in seven new child-care centres. The Environment Ministry says
this brings the total number of cases to 165 in 29 child-care centres in the
recent outbreak. Fifty-eight children have since recovered and have been
certified fit by doctors to return to their respective child-care
centres. One of the latest child-care centres to be investigated for an
outbreak of the disease is the YWMA Kindergarten in Old Jurong Road.
